The paper discusses the self-organizing properties of natural ecosystems and how they can be applied to digital ecosystems. This suggests that the paper may belong to the Multiagent Systems (cs.MA) sub-category, which deals with systems composed of multiple interacting agents. Additionally, the paper discusses the complex dynamic environment and spatial distributions that contribute to the self-organizing properties of natural ecosystems, which could also place it in the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) and Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-categories. The paper also discusses the digital business ecosystem (DBE) as an example architecture, which could place it in the Software Engineering (cs.SE) and Computer Engineering (cs.CE) sub-categories.
